blob
need "NEED-2026-004" {
  status = "identified"
  title = "Git Masquerading"
  goal = "Mos governance objects and refs live inside .git/ by default (GitStore backend), ensuring native forge compatibility, zero object duplication, and transparent git-push transport. The storage backend is configurable (git|fs|sqlite|encrypted) at repository creation with runtime migration between backends."
  slug = "git-masquerading"
  urgency = "critical"
  sensation = "Every governance artifact Mos manages today sits outside Git's object model, making git push a partial snapshot. Git Masquerading eliminates this gap: .git/ becomes the single source of truth for both code and governance. Forges display Mos history natively. No special server, no second blob store, no sync drift."

  scope {
    includes = [
      "ObjectStore interface abstraction with pluggable backends",
      "GitStore backend: store governance blobs/trees/commits as Git objects in .git/objects/",
      "Ref management: governance refs under refs/mos/* in .git/",
      "FSStore backend: plain .mos/ filesystem storage for pure-mos mode",
      "SQLiteStore backend: single-file transactional storage",
      "EncryptedStore backend: tamper-proof signed archives",
      "Backend selection via config flag at repo creation",
      "Runtime migration between backends via mos vcs migrate",
      "go-git as the Git plumbing library (no shelling out)",
    ]
    excludes = [
      "Custom forge UI extensions",
      "Git server implementation",
      "Remote collaboration protocol (covered by separate contracts)",
      "Branch/merge semantics (separate sprint scope)",
    ]
  }

  section "Principle" {
    text = """
Git Masquerading means Mos acts as a well-behaved Git citizen. Governance
objects are written as native Git blobs and trees. Governance commits are
Git commits. Governance refs live under refs/mos/ in .git/refs/.

From a forge perspective, the repository is a standard Git repo with
additional ref namespaces. git push transports governance history alongside
code history automatically. No special protocols, no sidecar stores."""
  }

  section "Backend Configurability" {
    text = """
The storage backend is a configuration flag, not an architectural decision.
A project can start with FSStore (human-readable .mos/ files), migrate to
GitStore when forge integration matters, or use SQLiteStore for compact
portable archives. Migration is lossless and reversible via mos vcs migrate.

The ObjectStore interface ensures all governance operations are backend-agnostic.
CLI commands, linters, harness, and audit work identically regardless of
which backend is active."""
  }

  acceptance {

    criterion "C1" {
      description = "An ObjectStore interface exists with Write, Read, Index, Pack, Unpack, Verify methods"
      verified_by = "harness"
    }

    criterion "C2" {
      description = "GitStore backend writes governance artifacts as Git blobs/trees in .git/objects/ and manages refs under refs/mos/*"
      verified_by = "harness"
    }

    criterion "C3" {
      description = "FSStore backend persists artifacts as plain .mos files with no external dependencies"
      verified_by = "harness"
    }

    criterion "C4" {
      description = "Backend selection is configurable via object_store.backend in config.mos"
      verified_by = "harness"
    }

    criterion "C5" {
      description = "mos vcs migrate converts between backends losslessly and reversibly"
      verified_by = "harness"
    }

    criterion "C6" {
      description = "All governance CLI commands work identically across all backends"
      verified_by = "harness"
    }

    criterion "C7" {
      description = "git push transports governance refs alongside code refs when using GitStore"
      verified_by = "harness"
    }
  }
}

